segments.text: We're in the office of the Austin Department of Planning and Growth Management, and I'm interviewing Luther Polnau, P-O-L-N-A-U.
And Luther is the principal planner with the department.
And Luther, how long have you been with this department?
this department since it began in 84 with the city since I was a student at the university in 1966.
Here in Austin University?
That's right.
I see.
And what were your studies at UT?
Architecture and graduate school.
What I'd like to concentrate on
First, this afternoon, Luther, is the period of transition between the Austin Tomorrow Plan project and the current Austin Plan project and the reorganization of the planning function in Austin.
And the last contact we had was with Dick Lilly prior to any discussions of reorganization of the planning functions.
And the Austin Tomorrow Plan had been readied for publication, but had not actually been published yet.
At the time that you interviewed Dick?
Exactly.
So the plan was published in 1980.
Then it must have been 79.
That's a long period to cover.
You can do it.
Well, let's see.
In what way are you interested in what the city was doing with planning or what the department was doing?
What the... How the reorganization occurred.
What led to the reorganization of the planning department?
Who initiated that?
I think there was probably...
some difficulty in enforcing the Awesome Tomorrow Competence Plan and interpreting it and seeing that it was very broad and it could be interpreted in very many ways.
And there were a lot of folks in town who

probably felt that it should not be implemented or should not be followed very strictly, that there should be some other planning procedures that, if it were strictly interpreted, I suppose there was a feeling that it was too restrictive, the growth corridor concept in particular.
As a matter of fact, it was not long after the plan was adopted that the council approved Motorola's plant out in the Oak Hill area, a location that was really contrary to the desires of the plan.
Did the council adopt the plan?
Yes, it was adopted.
It was adopted, but the plan, as most plans in Texas, are advisory.
This plan was advisory.
There's no requirement that it be followed.
The change, I suppose, in...

the way the department was organized came through both a, I guess, a perception that the plan wasn't being followed in the private sector, probably that it shouldn't be strictly adhered to, that it was too restrictive, and by the same token,

feeling that there needed to be a change, more authority or more power or more attention paid to master planning in terms of the way the city was organized, the structure of the department in particular.
And there was a group that put together a proposal for a new
planning department.
What group was that?
It was called Metro Austin.
I think the group is still in existence.
Is it a citizens group?
Yes.
Did that come out of the groups of neighborhood councils that had been working as a
as a citizens' group with the Austin Tomorrow Plan project?
No, the Metro Austin group was only primarily business-oriented.
I see.
One of the reasons that...
The only criticism I had heard of the Austin Tomorrow report, printed report, was that it was a bit vague in the sense that it...
didn't have any map, any diagram of what the adoption of policies would lead to in terms of location of activities.
It didn't have a land use plan.
It did have a map that identified priority development areas.
And the
The high growth area, the growth corridor, as it was known, was delineated on a map.
And that in itself was a bit of a problem for people to follow and to enforce.
One of the, as I understand it, one of the city councilmen requested directly through the city manager at that time that a planned diagram
be formulated that the council could receive and act on.
Are you aware of anything like that?
What do you mean, a plan diagram?
A plan, a land use element for the plan drawn.
I don't recall.
I don't recall that.
Okay.
I'd heard that, and I didn't know what the status of that was.
It was secondhand information for me.
Not that I'm aware of.
If you look at it from this reorganization, the restructuring of the planning department from an internal perspective, it seemed that
The folks that were involved with comprehensive planning were more involved in supporting the zoning and subdivision planners.
Once the plan was adopted,

Austin was on sort of a growth spurt that began probably in the late 70s, really picked up the rate of growth at three and three and a half percent in the late 70s and began to pick up to the point where by some people's account in 84 and 85 was double digit annual growth rate.
That sort of spurt in development with a staff that was smaller instead of larger resulted in comprehensive planning section.
The folks that were supposed to be watching out for the master plan really to be served more as support for special studies for zoning and subdivision activity.
And one of the
goals of the reorganization was to sort of get comprehensive planning back on track and give it some importance.

Restructuring the departments was to have the planning and growth management department perform that function as a separate department so that it would not be sucked into the day-to-day planning activities.
It's all too easy to do.
Yeah.
And organizationally, the department was to report directly to the manager.

And theoretically, at least at the time that it was being structured, the thought was that that sort of reporting structure would give the department a bit of an edge over other departments in terms of its role in coordinating the activities so that there would be some coordination and mutual supporting.
Where do the other departments report?
The way it's actually working there are assistant city managers that each of the departments report to.
So they certainly would put planning then in a more or less coordinated role.
Theoretically.
Potentially.
Yeah.
But as it actually happened, I think
planning is just another, or planning and growth management is another one of the departments that reports directly to an assistant city manager.
So the reorganization, at least ostensibly, was to do that.
Okay.
What is the size of your staff now in this particular department?
Must be around 45.
Of those, how many would you say were planners?
The other division is primarily the computer folks, the land-based information system that's being developed.
Probably about...
12 folks over there, 13 folks, and we probably have 20, 20 times.
That's about right.
You have to look at an organization chart to see exactly what it is.
Yeah.

Can you describe the general approach taken and the organization that is available now for the Austin Plan project and how this might differ from the Austin Tomorrow work that was done under Dick Lilly's administration?
The major difference is that the Austin Plan is...

enforceable not too long after the department was reorganized got some new folks in from Florida Florida is one of the states that has mandatory planning required compliance as part of the state law and Texas of course doesn't have that but as home rule cities go home rule charters are fairly

And shortly after the reorganization and bringing on board these folks, there was a charter election amendment to the charter that required the adoption of a comprehensive plan, specified the elements that are in that comprehensive plan, and required compliance of all the city's action to the comprehensive plan.

What that really means is that... We'll make sure to see what happens, but what it means is that the council, or anyone else for that matter, will have to... All the actions that the city takes will have to be in conformance with the comprehensive plan.
What if the council does what they did before with Motorola?
I suppose as any charter amendment or charter violation, I suppose a citizen can take the city to court or whatever.
I suppose that's the way charter violations are dealt with.
I would suspect that that would be the case.
But I think the situation here is that
There has to be a certain amount of flexibility, and I think what we look at in terms of what's going to happen here is

the comprehensive plan will allow some sort of predictability and consistency in action, but the plan can be amended, and it's intended that there would be amendments so that we get, before there is an action taken that is contrary to the comprehensive plan, discussion about amendment and its overall effect will occur.
And it has a couple advantages in that sense, in that...
Yes.

If the city is faced with a decision about a particular issue, the decision regarding that issue, if it involves a plan amendment, will require a more comprehensive view of the impact of that particular issue or decision.
And it will be less subject, I think, ideally, to the sort of incremental, narrow decisions that, at least ideally,
occurred in the past.

Well, that would mean then that the city, if, for example, something like a Motorola situation presented itself to the city in the future, then the city, if it were in conflict with the adopted plan, then the city would have to go through the hearing process for revising the plan, which would bring it before the public for discussion and so forth.
And then after readopting the plan in a new form, they'd have to

revise the zoning ordinance to accommodate uh the changes in the comprehensive plan right the other the other thing key to that is not only well i started to say not only are we going to have to amend the master plan and go through that public hearing process and see things in context but uh
interpretation of whether or not an issue or decision is in conformance with the plan is going to be a little bit more easy than it would have been with the old Austin Tomorrow Plan.
That plan was, as you mentioned before, very general.
There were some internal conflicts in it so that you could
almost come up with any position on an issue and find some statement in the plan that would support that position.
This plan, we're hoping, will have a little less
less broad dictates in it.
It will have a certain direction.
Yeah, there will be a land use element and a land use map, for instance.
And transportation?
It'll have all the classic components.
Public facilities.
Right.
That's very interesting to me as a kind of a traditionalist in planning.
We needn't go into that.
I'm not here to interview myself.

But that's quite a departure, because when I talked with Dick Lilly about this at conferences and when he was a guest at A&M in our department, I asked him why it was that the Austin Tomorrow Project seemed to be heading toward a policies document.
rather than a comprehensive plan.
And he said, well, he wasn't sure that the staff could put together a comprehensive plan.
And I thought he was kidding, frankly.
But I'm not so sure.
It was to know.
And we'll have to see now what comes out of this new project, because I would wonder about that statement.
I think that the staff here is quite capable of putting together a comprehensive plan.
Yeah, I would think so too, probably.
But at that time, of course, policy plans were very fashionable then.
Everybody had to have a policy plan.
If you didn't have a policy plan, you weren't on the cutting edge of planning.
Yeah, that's where the limelight...
Yes, and it was almost sort of a plan for planners in a sense, because that's what you come out with.
If there is any glory in planning, that's what planners are looking for, the glory or sort of innovative approaches.
I think there is a cost to that sort of thing that you take for granted the very basics, the foundation of planning, and try to get to something better, something...

something perhaps more exciting or something broader or whatever, you lose the very basic requirements of coordinating facilities, of making sure the various arms of the city are working in concert, and that it does do the things that it's supposed to for the private sector and for the public sector.
that we may be on sort of a pendulum and be going back to that too far.
I don't know, but I think it was missing in the past, in the recent past.
It was interesting because the same thing happened in Oakland, California.
They were putting together a document that had a long list of goals, objectives, and policies, but no planned diagrams.
for either circulation or land use or public utilities.
And they were directed by the city council to complete their work and to indicate what the consequences would be geographically of adopting that set of goals, objectives, and policies.
So they had to go back to the drafting board again to do that.
And here, that didn't happen.
What did happen, it seems to me, and correct me if I'm wrong,

It meant that the whole department was reorganized and that, as you pointed out, it was reorganized essentially to clarify the essential differences between current planning on a day-to-day basis and long-range comprehensive planning so that long-range comprehensive planning wouldn't be drained
a way to do the day-to-day tasks that should be handled elsewhere.
That's the reorganization.
The reorganization also was sort of a vehicle, a tool, for doing a new comprehensive plan, which was needed also.
Because we had a comprehensive plan and
We did not implement it.
We had several failed bond elections that resulted in our not being able to extend utilities in the areas that were called for in the comprehensive plan.
Private developers, there was a period of several years in the early 80s where the utilities that were extended were extended through our municipal utility districts.
The districts were created wherever the land could be had regardless of where the comprehensive plan called for development to occur.
By the time 8384 came about, we found ourselves having more development commitments without any regard to the comprehensive plan development commitments on the part of the private sector.
on the part of the city and having to respond to where the need was.
And we were in a situation where we had a comprehensive plan that was totally contrary to what was going on, what had occurred.
the need for the city to respond and take stock of itself.
I know that Lily was very upset about the proliferation of muds and what that was doing to frustrate the plan.
And then shortly after he commented on this at some APA meetings, Kent Butler published his paper in the Implanting Magazine.
which was quite a good paper, I thought.
Yeah, it was a strange time because we found the city was growing by leaps and bounds, population development, but the city itself was not able to respond because of the failed bond elections.
The private sector found a way to do it, and in finding a way to do it,

not only made things in a way simpler for them, they didn't have to comply with the comprehensive plan, practically speaking, but they also, through MUDS, there's sort of a market advantage because of the financial, the financing advantages to the developer and MUDS.
It was a necessity at first to put together MUDS, and it became a desirable way to develop later on.
They could take an end run around the city that way.
Essentially.
But, I don't know, the city...

The city began to use the contractual agreements with the MUDs to get some concessions out of the private sector in terms of specific land use requirements, public facilities that were donated, that sort of thing.
So gradually, there began to be a trade-off also.
And I think development standards for streets
I think we got some pretty good deals out of that.
Okay, now that that phase is over and you're into a new phase of planning for Austin, and this, by the way, is one of many comprehensive plans that have been prepared for Austin,
starting with, I think, the first one done by Hal Wise right after the Second World War.
Well, 1928 was actually the first one.
Kockenfeller.
Kockenfeller in 1928.
I wonder if there are any copies of that document that one could photocopy or refer to.
There probably are in the Austin Travis County Collection in the History Center.
They won't let me into the stacks.
to do research.
I have to go through the current catalog.
Let me just...

I was starting to say that there seemed to be a very strong position on the part of the business and development community, because Austin was growing such leaps and bounds, that the Austin Tomorrow comprehensive plan was stifling, was no growth sort of plan, and there was a strong move to
have another plan or to growth corridors.
Some of the terms that were used in the Austin Tomorrow Plan were dirty words.
And there was a strong feeling that we needed to have another plan or not use that plan.
There was a push to have a land use
map or land use element developed as part of an amendment to the Austin Tomorrow Plan.
Some way to get out of what at least a fairly large segment of the community, the business community anyway, felt was too confining a growth border concept.
unrealistic, no growth concept at the time that Austin was growing so fast.
And this was largely by the business community?
Yes.
Business, developers, builders, that growth-related community.
So as a consequence now, the new approach to the Austin Plan, I gather, has

acknowledged those feelings on the part of the community, business community and others, and has moved ahead with what I would term a classical approach toward a comprehensive plan, namely a plan that's composed of three essential elements of land use, transportation, and public facilities.
more elements in that.
There are 10 or 12 elements, but it is of that ilk, yes.
And I think the notion here is

One that is not so rigid in terms of defining a growth border, an area where we should grow in terms of a guiding concept of a plan, but of a land use element that coordinates the basic utility services and roads and that sort of thing.

The environmental constraints that were paramount in the Austin Tomorrow Plan are certainly recognized in this plan, but I think there's probably a broader recognition of engineering or design mitigation to deal with the environmental concerns, and not so much of what was perceived at the time
no development outside the growth corridor.
And although that was not the intent or the way the plan was to work, that's the popular interpretation of it.
You had definite no development zones.
That was the perception that the public had.
That's the perception.
That's not what the plan called for, but got a dirty name because of that.
OK.
I'll ask Norman about timing.
But I wanted to ask you what other elements are considered for the awesome plan project now, in addition to the three basics?
OK, you mentioned the transportation, land use, public facilities.
There's public services also, and public buildings as well.
Environment, economics, economic development, housing, health and social services.
cultural affairs, urban design.
I'm sure I left out one or two, but well, OK.
Question on your transportation element.
Austin has been going through the agonies of debate over its airport for about 20 years to my knowledge.
And before that, I don't know.
Is the Austin plan going to solve that problem?
I doubt it.

There's an airport commission that's seated right now, and I think you may have to ask Norm how this goes, but my perception of what would happen with this is that there are probably some key players, key...
factors involved that would be dealt with by the airport commission city council participants in the transportation as well as the land use component of this plan that all be involved together
But I think the airport issue is a political issue.
It's not necessarily a planning issue.
I think there have been plenty of reports that say the area that it's in right now is such that it can't reasonably be expanded without paying a hell of a price on existing housing and development.
If you look at it from that position, I think it needs to be moved somewhere.
But that's an opinion.
On circulation, the officials at Texas A&M from the top on down are very concerned about the lack of good highway facilities between College Station and Austin.
And they are working very closely with the State Division of Highways and Transportation to upgrade circulation between the two, largely because of the two universities.
are you going to be proposing in the Austin plan for any new major links between College Station and Austin?
For example, particularly, let me point out that the only two ways in and out of Austin now from the east are going either north to the north end of the city or the south end of the city.
There's nothing that goes right into the middle of the city that I'm aware of.
Not as a major road.
Those are the only two state highways that exist throughout Dallas.
Any of the others are just county roads.
I'm not aware of anything.
We have, I suppose, Austin Transportation Study.
And...
The major interest right now, I think, is north-south, and most recently an alternative to I-35 to San Antonio.
You're at capacity now on 35, aren't you?
Yes, there's talk about double-decking beyond what we already have.
Double-decking the double-decker?
No, extending the double-deck.
Extending it.
Yes, on the way out to Bend White in the south.
They're in the process now of widening the northern portion.
Okay, is there anything else you'd like to comment on?
with regard to the project.
No?
OK.
I can't think of anything.
Thank you very much.
OK. Good afternoon.
This is the 21st of November, 1986.
We're in the office of Norman Standoffer, the planning director.
for the Department of Planning and Growth Management of the city of Austin.
And Norman, I'd like to start out by asking you, what were the influences on your life as a planner that brought you from Florida, where you were, to Austin, Texas?
I'm dying of smoking.
I guess at the time I considered coming to Austin, I was extremely skeptical of coming back to this part of the world.
because I didn't really believe there was much to be done for planting in the Southwest.
You say coming back, you were here... Well, I wasn't in Texas, but I was in Oklahoma for a good deal of my career before I went to Florida.
I equate the great Southwest as the desert for planting.
I always did during my career because it just wasn't part of the mandatory planting movement.
It wasn't much innovative, in my opinion, professionally happening.
at least not what I was looking for.
I felt my career and my view of planning really matured after spending nearly 10, 12 years in Oklahoma.
Where were you in Oklahoma?
I was in Oklahoma City, basically, in central Oklahoma.
I went to the university, got my master's degree, came out of school in the mid-60s.
Weren't a lot of planners around in those days in Oklahoma.
Became a planning director as my first job in a little suburban community of Central Oklahoma, Midwest City.
And as many people did in those days, you ran a one-man, you know, planning and zoning shop.
And basically stayed around Central Oklahoma, moved to Oklahoma City as assistant director and eventually as director.
I finally got to the midlife crisis of the early 40s and tried to figure out what I was going to do with my life.
I had accomplished significant things I thought were mine in Oklahoma City and was at the crossroads of what I wanted to do with my life.
And I started my own consulting firm.
Got into rehabilitation of old Victorian homes and that kind of thing, thinking I was going to find a solution to renovation of the inner city by myself.
In Oklahoma City.
Yeah.
Went through the epic problems of the first time interest rates went from 10% to 14%, and that ended that venture.
Went to South Florida and really learned what planning was all about.
I spent nearly five years in Broward County, Florida, which is well documented as one of the fastest growth urban areas in the United States.
It grew from 85,000 people in 1950 to over a million in 1980.
And it was just a phenomenal urban laboratory.
It was a very innovative place to do planning.
in terms of it was the first governmental unit in the state of Florida to adopt in its charter, interestingly enough, a mandatory planning charter.
It came out of a grassroots charter movement of the people of the area and followed two years later by the Florida Mandatory Planning Act.
It was a unique kind of intergovernmental system.
It wasn't like Metro Dade or Nashville Davidson in its charter, but it was metropolitan in its planning and regulation, but not in other service provisions of government.
It was a good start.
Yeah, and it was a very interesting challenge.
I got to Broward at the time the plan had been completed.
Was that an in-house job?
No, they had used consultants, but largely in-house.
And they had been wrestling for a couple of years over the implementation and regulatory streamlining part of making it function.
And I got the job of writing the Broward County Land Development Code, which was the tool and the vehicle that implemented the plan.
And that thing
That process, that entity, and the resulting litigations that came about with some of our innovations and impact fees and things like that were just, to me, were the top of my professional career.
And I was at the point, having put that to bed and had it working real well, Jim Duncan sitting there as one of my principal deputies running the thing, it just worked like a dream and
There wasn't any more challenge.
And all of a sudden, we were up at the conference.
I can't remember where the conference was.
Northeast somewhere, when we saw and heard the rumblings about the... Austin?
Austin, and everybody started figuring out what was going on in Austin.
Jim Duncan had told me about Austin all his life because Jim had been from here originally.
Went to UT, worked here as a planning intern, that kind of thing.
They said all his life, if he ever got the opportunity, there's only one place he'd want to settle, and that's Austin, Texas.
And he got real interested, because at the same time they advertised his job that he took, they advertised this job.
They broke Dick's department into two departments.
And it was just so phenomenal that the two job ads were tailor-made.
He's regulatory day to day zoning nuts and bolts.
That's his forte, planning and automation, which were the the issues that they were building around this department and what we've done here were my forte.
It was just, you know, it's like, we're the people so we applied I was a little less skeptical of it because I was my ingrained attitudes about
Leaving a mandatory planning state, a state where the legislation, the litigation, and the momentum for planning were so perfect.
I just consider that the greatest planning environment in the world.
But I was 45-plus years old.
I felt I had capped my career.
And I said, the only other thing I want to do in the public sector is make it work in a non-mandatory planning state.
Well, when we came through the interview process down here with the city manager, they were really talking about the possibilities of stretching the limits with Austin.
And we learned about the problems of Austin and the polarities and the pro-growth, no-growth and the dramatic problems they were having here.
But the interest in the then city council and the manager in perhaps trying to do something through our Home Rule Charter.
Who was the city manager then?
It was Jorge Carrasco, the current city manager.
He was, I see.
He had just been appointed six or eight months before that.
And who was the manager before him?
That was when Dick Ernie was here.
Gosh, it slips my mind.
Wasn't Dan Davidson another fellow right after that?
Well, there was somebody between Davidson and Carrasco.
Yes.
I can't recall his name.
But knowing the strong home rule power of Texas City, well, there's always that possibility that you can set a mandatory context in our home rule charter.
I've talked with my friends and peers back here for years.
APA chapter wants to go get the state legislature to do something about the Planning Act.
And I said, yeah, forget it.
Do it in your own charter.
Do it at home.
If you can't do it at home, don't expect the legislature to do it for you.
You've got all the power of home rule authority to do it just like it happened in Florida.
And don't worry about it.
Don't wait for the state legislature, rural dominated, real estate dominated, bank dominated, to give you planning mandates.
Our manager and our counsel said, we'll think about doing that.
Well, that convinced me if I'm going to do one more stint in the public sector, what better way than to pull it off in the middle of Texas.
And that was kind of the challenge.
Okay, that's very interesting that that challenge, and then of course it worked out.
The question is open until we finish.
When you were in Florida...
Did you know Dan O'Connell?
Oh, yes.
Well, Dan and I are pretty good friends.
Oh.
And we knew each other when he, first of all, had wondered if he would pursue a PhD at Texas A&M or University of Washington.
Right.
Well, you know what happened with the situation at University of Washington, and I, of course, had known him up there, too, and I could tell he was getting disenchanted.
And then we kept in correspondence after he returned to Florida.
And I guess he's still in the governor's office.
Yeah, should be figuring out what he's doing himself since the governor's going to the Senate.
I've been meaning to try to call him and find out what's going on.
We keep in contact every three or four months.
He's a very good man.
If you talk to him before I do, say hello.
He sure is.
He's very inventive and got lots of energy.
As a matter of fact, we got Dan in here.
That's right.
He mentioned he was coming.
I got here in September.
Duncan got here in August.
We were faced with this big Northwest plan fiasco here.
And in the process of doing that plan, we were also working behind the scenes with the council, who said, all right, take a shot at giving us a mandatory charter.
And we got Dan O'Connell in here as a consultant.
to do a big report, give them the legislative legal bases for doing these kinds of things, and to draft our charter.

And we did that in about a 45-day period, put it on the, gave it to the council, had one hearing, they didn't even know what they were reading, put it on with 18 other items on the referendum, and it passed by 68%.
